In this appendix, we will introduce stacks on spaces, which we want to think of as sheaves valued in a (2,1)-category instead of 1-category. Stacks are of great interest to us because they provide a gateway to thinking about higher categories, through studying an object similar to sheaves, which we discussed a lot in this course. Also, many of the objects we studied in this course can be used to define stacks, as we will see with the stack of principal bundles, allowing us to revisit some of these topics and apply our knowledge. Before giving a concrete definition for stacks on spaces, let's recall the definition of a sheaf of sets on some topological space $X$.
\begin{definition}
A functor $F: \Open(X)^{\op} \to \Set$ is a \textit{presheaf} of sets on $X$. We say that $F$ is a \textit{sheaf} if for every open subset $U \subseteq X$ and every open cover $\mathcal{U} = \{U_i\}$ of $U$, the unique map
$$
F(U) \xrightarrow{\cong} \lim \left( \prod F(U_i) \rightrightarrows \prod F(U_i \cap U_j) \right)
$$
guaranteed by the universality of the limit is a bijection.
\end{definition}
Recall that we also similarly defined a sheaf of abelian groups on $X$.
\begin{definition}
A functor $F: \Open(X)^{\op} \to \Ab$ is a \textit{presheaf} of sets on $X$. We say that $F$ is a \textit{sheaf} if for every open subset $U \subseteq X$ and every open cover $\mathcal{U} = \{U_i\}$ of $U$, the unique map
$$
F(U) \xrightarrow{\cong} \lim \left( \prod F(U_i) \rightrightarrows \prod F(U_i \cap U_j) \right)
$$
guaranteed by the universality of the limit is an isomorphism of abelian groups.
\end{definition}
\begin{remark}
The key point to observe here is that $\Set$ and $\Ab$ are both 1-categories. Note that 1-categories are what we have just been calling categories in this course. For any 1-category $\mathcal{C}$, we define a sheaf on $X$ valued in $\mathcal{C}$ using the same definition.
\end{remark}
\begin{definition}
A functor $F: \Open(X)^{\op} \to \mathcal{C}$ is a \textit{presheaf} on $X$ valued in $\mathcal{C}$. We say that $F$ is a \textit{sheaf} if for every open subset $U \subseteq X$ and every open cover $\mathcal{U} = \{U_i\}$ of $U$, the unique map
$$
F(U) \xrightarrow{\cong} \lim \left( \prod F(U_i) \rightrightarrows \prod F(U_i \cap U_j) \right)
$$
guaranteed by the universality of the limit is an isomorphism in $\mathcal{C}$.
\end{definition}
\begin{definition}
We refer to the condition that we have an isomorphism
$$
F(U) \xrightarrow{\cong} \lim \left( \prod F(U_i) \rightrightarrows \prod F(U_i \cap U_j) \right)
$$
as the \emph{sheaf condition}. Therefore, a sheaf is a presheaf $F: \Open(X)^\op \to \mathcal{C}$ that satisfies the sheaf condition.
\end{definition}
\begin{question}
    Now, the question we want to ask ourselves is, what changes if we consider presheaves valued in something other than a 1-category? What if we have a presheaf valued in a 2-category or a (2,1)-category?
\end{question}
Before going any further, we should define what we mean by a 2-category or a (2,1)-category.
\begin{definition}
This definition is from \cite{kellystreet}. A 2-category $\mathcal{K}$ is the data of objects or 0-cells $A, B, \cdots$, 1-morphisms or 1-cells $f: A \to B$, and 2-morphisms or 2-cells 
\[\begin{tikzcd}
	A && B
	\arrow[""{name=0, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "g"', curve={height=6pt}, from=1-1, to=1-3]
	\arrow[""{name=1, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "f", shift left=3, curve={height=-6pt}, from=1-1, to=1-3]
	\arrow["\alpha", Rightarrow, from=1, to=0]
\end{tikzcd}\]
The objects and 1-morphisms form a 1-category (or just a category) $\mathcal{K}_0$ called the \emph{underlying category} of $\mathcal{K}$, with identity morphisms $\id_A: A \to A$. For fixed objects $A, B$, the 1-morphisms $A \to B$ and 2-morphisms between them form a 1-category $K(A, B)$, where the 1-morphisms are the objects and the 2-morphisms are the morphisms. The composition of morphisms in this category is known as vertical composition, denoted
\[\begin{tikzcd}
	A && B
	\arrow[""{name=0, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "g"'{pos=0.2}, from=1-1, to=1-3]
	\arrow[""{name=1, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "f", shift left=3, curve={height=-12pt}, from=1-1, to=1-3]
	\arrow[""{name=2, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "h"', shift right=3, curve={height=12pt}, from=1-1, to=1-3]
	\arrow["\alpha", Rightarrow, from=1, to=0]
	\arrow["\beta", Rightarrow, from=0, to=2]
\end{tikzcd}\]
The vertical composite $f \Rightarrow h$ above is denoted by $\beta \cdot \alpha$, or just $\beta \alpha$ when there is no cause for confusion horizontal composition we define below. The identity morphisms in $\mathcal{K}(A, B)$ are denoted by
\[\begin{tikzcd}
	A && B
	\arrow[""{name=0, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "f"', curve={height=6pt}, from=1-1, to=1-3]
	\arrow[""{name=1, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "f", shift left=3, curve={height=-6pt}, from=1-1, to=1-3]
	\arrow["{\text{id}_f}", Rightarrow, from=1, to=0]
\end{tikzcd}\]
Note that we can also define horizontal composition of 2-morphisms, where the composite of 
\[\begin{tikzcd}
	A && B && B && C
	\arrow[""{name=0, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "g"', curve={height=6pt}, from=1-1, to=1-3]
	\arrow[""{name=1, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "f", shift left=3, curve={height=-6pt}, from=1-1, to=1-3]
