Recall that we defined 2-functors as functors between 2-categories. However, in the previous example, we had $F: \CRing \to \Cat$, where $\CRing$ is a 1-category, which we stated was a weak 2-functor. We briefly addressed this in the example, but it is worth mentioning apart from the example as its own remark. For any 1-category $\mathcal{C}$, we can consider it as a 2-category (and in particular a (2,1)-category) by considering the 2-morphisms to be only the identity 2-morphism for each 1-morphism.
