Now that we are familiar with all the relevant definitions related to 2-categories, let's go back to our question and consider what happens if we consider presheaves valued in something other than a 1-category. In particular, we will consider presheaves valued in the (2,1)-category of groupoids, that is, functors $F: \Open(X)^{\op} \to \Grpd$. This naturally leads us to another question.
\begin{question}
What would it mean for the presheaf $F: \Open(X)^{\op} \to \Grpd$ to be a sheaf? In other words, what is the sheaf condition for presheaves valued in $\Grpd$? Can we use the same sheaf condition as for presheaves valued in a 1-category, and if not, what should it be?
\end{question}
It turns out that the sheaf condition for presheaves valued in a 1-category in insufficient, so we will need a new condition for a presheaf $F: \Open(X)^{\op} \to \Grpd$ to be considered as a sheaf valued in $\Grpd$. This new condition leads us directly to the long awaited definition of a stack, which we want to think of as a sheaf of groupoids on a space $X$.
\begin{definition}
Let $X$ be a topological space, and $F: \Open(X)^{\op} \to \Grpd$ be a weak 2-functor (a presheaf of groupoids on $X$). We say that $F$ is a \textit{stack} (a sheaf) if for every open subset $U \subseteq X$ and every open cover $\mathcal{U} = \{U_i\}$ of $U$, the functor
\[\begin{tikzcd}[cramped]
	{F(U)} & {\lim \bigg( \prod F(U_i)} & {\prod F(U_i \cap U_j)} & {\prod F(U_i \cap U_j \cap U_k) \bigg)}
	\arrow["\cong", from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow[shift right, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[shift left, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[from=1-3, to=1-4]
	\arrow[shift left=2, from=1-3, to=1-4]
	\arrow[shift right=2, from=1-3, to=1-4]
\end{tikzcd}\]
guaranteed by the universal property of the $2$-limit in $\Grpd$ is an equivalence of categories.
\end{definition}
\begin{definition}
Given a space $X$, an open subset $U \subset X$ and a cover $\mathcal{U} = \{U_i\}$ of $U$, we call 
\[\begin{tikzcd}[cramped]
	{\lim \bigg( \prod F(U_i)} & {\prod F(U_i \cap U_j)} & {\prod F(U_i \cap U_j \cap U_k) \bigg)}
	\arrow[shift right, from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow[shift left, from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow[from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[shift left=2, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[shift right=2, from=1-2, to=1-3]
\end{tikzcd}\]
the category of descent data $\Desc(\mathcal{U}, F)$. Then, we say $F$ is a stack if $F(U)$ is equivalent to the category of descent data; that is, if we have an equivalence of categories $F(U) \cong \Desc(\mathcal{U}, F)$.
\end{definition}
\begin{definition}
We refer to the condition that we have an equivalence of categories
\[\begin{tikzcd}[cramped]
	{F(U)} & {\lim \bigg( \prod F(U_i)} & {\prod F(U_i \cap U_j)} & {\prod F(U_i \cap U_j \cap U_k) \bigg)}
	\arrow["\cong", from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow[shift right, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[shift left, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[from=1-3, to=1-4]
	\arrow[shift left=2, from=1-3, to=1-4]
	\arrow[shift right=2, from=1-3, to=1-4]
\end{tikzcd}\]
as the stack condition, so a stack is a functor $F: \Open(X)^\op \to \Grpd$ that satisfies the stack condition.
\end{definition}
\begin{example}
Let's consider what the stack condition tells us in a simple example. Suppose \( X = U_1 \cup U_2 \) is an open cover, so we have a two element open cover $\mathcal{U} = \{ U_1, U_2 \}$ of $X$. If $F$ is a stack, we have an equivalence of categories
    \[ F(X) \xrightarrow{\cong} \lim \left(F(U_1) \times F(U_2) \rightrightarrows F(U_1 \cap U_2) \right), \]
    where we omit the triple overlap term since there are no triple overlaps in the open cover. We will rewrite this 2-equalizer as the 2-pullback of the following diagram, where \( E = \lim \left(F(U_1) \times F(U_2) \rightrightarrows F(U_1 \cap U_2) \right) \),
    \[\begin{tikzcd}
    	E & {F(U_1)} \\
    	{F(U_2)} & {F(U_1 \cap U_2)}
    	\arrow[from=1-1, to=1-2]
    	\arrow[from=1-1, to=2-1]
    	\arrow["\lrcorner"{anchor=center, pos=0.125}, draw=none, from=1-1, to=2-2]
    	\arrow["\psi", from=1-2, to=2-2]
    	\arrow["\phi"', from=2-1, to=2-2]
    \end{tikzcd} \]
    Therefore, \( E \) is a groupoid with:
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item objects $(a,b,\alpha)$ such that \( a \in \text{Ob}(F(U_1)) \), \( b \in \text{Ob}(F(U_2))\), and \( \alpha: \psi(a) \xrightarrow{\cong} \phi(b) \) in $F(U_1 \cap U_2)$, where $\psi$ and $\phi$ are the restrictions induced by the inclusions $U_1 \cap U_2 \to U_1$ and $U_1 \cap U_2 \to U_2$ respectively,
        \item morphisms $(a_1,b_1,\alpha_1) \xrightarrow{f} (a_2,b_2,\alpha_2)$, which consist of the data of isomorphisms $a_1 \xrightarrow[\cong]{f_a} a_2$ and $b_1 \xrightarrow[\cong]{f_b} b_2$
        so that
        \[\begin{tikzcd}
        	{\psi(a_1)} && {\psi(a_2)} \\
        	\\
        	{\phi(b_1)} && {\phi(b_2)}
        	\arrow["{{\psi(f_a)}}", from=1-1, to=1-3]
        	\arrow["\cong"{description}, shift right=2, draw=none, from=1-1, to=1-3]
        	\arrow["{{\alpha_1}}"', from=1-1, to=3-1]
        	\arrow["\cong"{description}, shift left=3, draw=none, from=1-1, to=3-1]
        	\arrow["{{\alpha_2}}", from=1-3, to=3-3]
        	\arrow["\cong"{description}, shift right=3, draw=none, from=1-3, to=3-3]
        	\arrow["{{\phi(f_b)}}"', from=3-1, to=3-3]
        	\arrow["\cong"{description}, shift left=2, draw=none, from=3-1, to=3-3]
        \end{tikzcd}\]
        commutes.
    \end{enumerate}
    The stack condition tells us that \( F(X) \) is equivalent to \( E \) in this simple case of a $2$-object cover. 
\end{example}
\begin{remark}
Note that in the previous example with a 2-object cover, the category of descent data
$$
\Desc(\{ U_1, U_2\}, F) = \lim \left(F(U_1) \times F(U_2) \rightrightarrows F(U_1 \cap U_2) \right)
$$
does not contain the triple overlap term $F(U_i \cap U_j \cap U_k)$, and so the stack condition looks just like the sheaf condition for a sheaf valued in a 1-category.
\end{remark}
\begin{question}
This might lead one to ask, why do we need to consider triple overlaps in the stack condition, why can't we just consider double overlaps like the sheaf condition? Let's consider the example of a 3-object cover to see why.
\end{question}
\begin{example}
Suppose \( X = U_1 \cup U_2 \cup U_3 \) such that \( U_{12} = U_1 \cap U_2, U_{13} = U_1 \cap U_3, U_{23} = U_2 \cap U_3 \text{ and } U_{123} = U1 \cap U_2 \cap U_3 \) are all nonempty. If \( F \) is a stack, then we have an equivalence of categories
\[\begin{tikzcd}[cramped]
	{F(X)} & {\lim \bigg( F(U_1)F(U_2)F(U_3)} & {\prod F(U_{12}) F(U_{13}) F(U_{23})} & {\prod F(U_{123}) \bigg)}
	\arrow["\cong", from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow[shift right, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[shift left, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[from=1-3, to=1-4]
	\arrow[shift left=2, from=1-3, to=1-4]
	\arrow[shift right=2, from=1-3, to=1-4]
\end{tikzcd}\]
However, let's first consider what happens if we ignore the triple overlap \( U_{123} \): define
\[ E = \lim\left( F(U_1) \times F(U_2) \times F(U_3) \rightrightarrows F(U_{12}) \times F(U_{13}) \times F(U_{23}) \right), \]
that is, \( E \) is the limit of the following diagram.
\[\begin{tikzcd}
	{F(U_3)} &&&& {F(U_2)} \\
	&& {F(U_1)} \\
	{F(U_{13})} &&&& {F(U_{12})} \\
	&& {F(U_{23})}
	\arrow["{R_{3,1}}"{description}, from=1-1, to=3-1]
	\arrow["{R_{3,2}}"{description, pos=0.3}, from=1-1, to=4-3]
	\arrow["{R_{2,3}}"{description, pos=0.3}, from=1-5, to=4-3]
	\arrow["{R_{1,3}}"{description, pos=0.3}, from=2-3, to=3-1]
	\arrow["{R_{1,2}}"{description, pos=0.3}, from=2-3, to=3-5]
    \arrow["{R_{2,1}}"{description}, from=1-5,to=3-5]
\end{tikzcd}\]
Then, we know that \( E \) is the groupoid with
\begin{enumerate}
    \item objects \( (a_1,a_2,a_3,\phi_{12},\phi_{13},\phi_{23}) \) such that \( a_i \in F(U_i)\) and
    \( \phi_{ij}: R_{i,j}(a_i) \xrightarrow{\cong} R_{j,i}(a_j), \) and
    \item morphisms \( (a_1,a_2,a_3,\phi_{12},\phi_{13},\phi_{23}) \xrightarrow{f} (a_1',a_2',a_3',\phi'_{12},\phi'_{13},\phi'_{23}) \), which are the data of
    \[ a_1 \xrightarrow{f_1} a_1', \qquad a_2 \xrightarrow{f_2} a_2', \qquad \text{ and} \qquad a_3 \xrightarrow{f_3} a_3' \]
    such that the following diagrams commute
    \[\begin{tikzcd}
    	{R_{1,2}(a_1)} && {R_{1,2}(a_1')} && {R_{1,3}(a_1)} && {R_{1,3}(a_1')} \\
    	\\
    	{R_{2,1}(a_2)} && {R_{2,1}(a_2')} && {R_{3,1}(a_3)} && {R_{3,1}(a_3')} \\
    	\\
    	&& {R_{2,3}(a_2)} && {R_{2,3}(a_2')} \\
    	\\
    	&& {R_{3,2}(a_3)} && {R_{3,2}(a_3')}
    	\arrow["{R_{1,2}(f_1)}", from=1-1, to=1-3]
    	\arrow["{\phi_{1,2}}"', from=1-1, to=3-1]
    	\arrow["\cong"{description}, shift left=2, draw=none, from=1-1, to=3-1]
    	\arrow["{\phi'_{1,2}}", from=1-3, to=3-3]
    	\arrow["\cong"{description}, shift right=2, draw=none, from=1-3, to=3-3]
    	\arrow["{R_{1,3}(f_1)}", from=1-5, to=1-7]
    	\arrow["{\phi_{1,3}}"', from=1-5, to=3-5]
    	\arrow["\cong"{description}, shift left=2, draw=none, from=1-5, to=3-5]
    	\arrow["{\phi'_{1,3}}", from=1-7, to=3-7]
    	\arrow["\cong"{description}, shift right=2, draw=none, from=1-7, to=3-7]
    	\arrow["{R_{2,1}(f_2)}"', from=3-1, to=3-3]
    	\arrow["{R_{3,1}(f_3)}"', from=3-5, to=3-7]
    	\arrow["{R_{2,3}(f_2)}", from=5-3, to=5-5]
    	\arrow["{\phi_{2,3}}"', from=5-3, to=7-3]
    	\arrow["\cong"{description}, shift left=2, draw=none, from=5-3, to=7-3]
    	\arrow["{\phi'_{2,3}}", from=5-5, to=7-5]
    	\arrow["\cong"{description}, shift right=2, draw=none, from=5-5, to=7-5]
    	\arrow["{R_{3,2}(f_3)}"', from=7-3, to=7-5]
    \end{tikzcd}.\]
    that is, \(\phi'_{i,j} \circ R_{i,j}(f_i) = R_{j,i}(f_j) \circ \phi_{i,j} \) for all $i < j$.
\end{enumerate}
Without any condition on triple overlaps, we have no reason to assume that the following hexagon commutes:
\[\begin{tikzcd}
    & {T_2(R_{13}(a_1))} && {T_3(R_{12}(a_1))} & \\
    \\
    {T_2(R_{31}(a_3))} &&&& {T_3(R_{21}(a_2))} \\
    \\
    & {T_1(R_{32}(a_3))} && {T_1(R_{23}(a_2))}
    \arrow["{=}"{description}, no head, from=1-2, to=1-4]
    \arrow["{\phi_{1,3}}"{description}, from=1-2, to=3-1]
    \arrow["{\phi_{1,2}}"{description}, from=1-4, to=3-5]
    \arrow["{=}"{description}, no head, from=3-1, to=5-2]
    \arrow["{=}"{description}, no head, from=3-5, to=5-4]
    \arrow["{\phi_{2,3}}"{description}, from=5-4, to=5-2]
\end{tikzcd}\]
However, it really should commute, so let's see if this is what we obtain by considering the triple overlaps. We now want to consider
\[\begin{tikzcd}
	{E=} & {\lim \bigg( F(U_1)F(U_2)F(U_3)} & {\prod F(U_{12}) F(U_{13}) F(U_{23})} & {\prod F(U_{123}) \bigg)}
	\arrow[shift right, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[shift left, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[from=1-3, to=1-4]
	\arrow[shift left=2, from=1-3, to=1-4]
	\arrow[shift right=2, from=1-3, to=1-4]
\end{tikzcd}\]
which is the limit of the following diagram
\[\begin{tikzcd}
    {F(U_3)} &&&& {F(U_2)} \\
    && {F(U_1)} \\
    {F(U_{13})} &&&& {F(U_{12})} \\
    && {F(U_{23})} \\
    \\
    && {F(U_{123})}
    \arrow["{R_{3,1}}"{description}, from=1-1, to=3-1]
    \arrow["{R_{3,2}}"{description, pos=0.3}, from=1-1, to=4-3]
    \arrow["{R_{2,1}}"{description}, from=1-5, to=3-5]
    \arrow["{R_{2,3}}"{description, pos=0.3}, from=1-5, to=4-3]
    \arrow["{R_{1,3}}"{description, pos=0.3}, from=2-3, to=3-1]
    \arrow["{R_{1,2}}"{description, pos=0.3}, from=2-3, to=3-5]
    \arrow["{T_2}"{description}, from=3-1, to=6-3]
    \arrow["{T_3}"{description}, from=3-5, to=6-3]
    \arrow["{T_1}"{description}, from=4-3, to=6-3]
\end{tikzcd}\]
Therefore, $E$ is the groupoid with
\begin{enumerate}
    \item objects \( (a_1,a_2,a_3, \phi_{12},\phi_{13},\phi_{23} ) \) such that \( a_i \in F(U_i), \phi_{ij}: R_{i,j}(a_i) \xrightarrow{\cong} R_{j,i}(a_j), \) and these satisfy the cocycle condition
    \[ \phi_{j,k} \circ \phi_{i,j} = \phi_{i,k} \text{; and} \]
    \item morphisms \( (a_1,a_2,a_3, \phi_{12},\phi_{13},\phi_{23}) \xrightarrow{f} (a'_1,a'_2,a'_3, \phi'_{12},\phi'_{13},\phi'_{23}) \) the data of
    \[ a_1 \xrightarrow{f_1} a'_1, \qquad a_2 \xrightarrow{f_1} a'_2, \qquad \text{and} \qquad a_3 \xrightarrow{f_1} a'_3 \]
    such that, like above, \( \phi'_{i,j} \circ R_{i,j}(f_i) = R_{j,i}(f_j) \circ \phi_{i,j} \).
\end{enumerate}
The cocycle condition on objects gives us that the desired hexagon commutes. This example illustrates what the category of descent datum is like and explains the importance of the triple overlaps being considered.
\end{example}
\begin{remark}
Before considering our first concrete example of a stack, we need to discuss some Grothendieck topology and the distinction between big site and the small site. For now, it suffices to note that the definition of a stack we gave above is for a small site, and there is a similar definition for a big site.
\end{remark}
\begin{definition}
Let $F: \Top^\op \ \to \Grpd$ be a weak 2-functor. We say that $F$ is a \textit{stack} if for every space $X$ and every open cover $\mathcal{U} = \{U_i\}$ of $X$, the functor
\[\begin{tikzcd}[cramped]
	{F(X)} & {\lim \bigg( \prod F(U_i)} & {\prod F(U_i \cap U_j)} & {\prod F(U_i \cap U_j \cap U_k) \bigg)}
	\arrow["\cong", from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow[shift right, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[shift left, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[from=1-3, to=1-4]
	\arrow[shift left=2, from=1-3, to=1-4]
	\arrow[shift right=2, from=1-3, to=1-4]
\end{tikzcd}\]
guaranteed by the universal property of the $2$-limit in $\Grpd$ is an equivalence of categories. 
\end{definition}
\begin{example}
Let's consider an example of a functor that satisfies the stack condition. Let $F: \Top^{\op} \to \Grpd$ be the functor sending a space $X$ to its groupoid of principal $G$ bundles $\Prin_{G}(X)$, and sending a continuous map $f: X \to Y$ to the functor $f^*: \Prin_{G}(Y) \to \Prin_{G}(X)$ defined as follows:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item On objects, $f^*$ sends $P \in \text{Ob}(\Prin_{G}(Y))$ to the pullback $X \times_{Y} P \in \text{Ob}(\Prin_{G}(X))$ of $P$ along $f$, seen as
    \[\begin{tikzcd}
    	{X \times_{Y} P} && P \\
    	\\
    	X && Y
    	\arrow[from=1-1, to=1-3]
    	\arrow[from=1-1, to=3-1]
    	\arrow["\lrcorner"{anchor=center, pos=0.125}, draw=none, from=1-1, to=3-3]
    	\arrow["\pi", two heads, from=1-3, to=3-3]
    	\arrow["f"', from=3-1, to=3-3]
    \end{tikzcd}\]
    \item On morphisms, which are all isomorphisms since $\Prin_{G}(Y)$ is a groupoid, $f^*$ sends $\varphi: P \xrightarrow[]{\cong} P'$ to the isomorphism $f^*\varphi : X \times_{Y} P \xrightarrow[]{\cong} X \times_{Y} P'$ defined by
    $$
    (x, p) \mapsto (x, \varphi(p)) = (f^*\varphi)(x,p).
    $$
    Note this is well-defined since \( \pi'(\varphi(p)) = \pi(p) = f(x). \)
\end{enumerate}

Given a cover \( \mathcal{U} = \{ U_i \}_{i \in I } \) of \( X \),
\[\begin{tikzcd}[cramped]
	{F(X)} & {\lim \bigg( \prod F(U_i)} & {\prod F(U_i \cap U_j)} & {\prod F(U_i \cap U_j \cap U_k) \bigg)}
	\arrow["\cong", from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow[shift right, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[shift left, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[from=1-3, to=1-4]
	\arrow[shift left=2, from=1-3, to=1-4]
	\arrow[shift right=2, from=1-3, to=1-4]
\end{tikzcd}\]
is the data of
\begin{enumerate}
    \item objects are collections of principal \( G \)-bundles \( (\pi_i,\phi_{i,j})_{i,j} \) with \( \pi_i: P_i \to U_i \) for each i and
    \[ \phi_{i,j} : R_{i,j}(\pi_i) \xrightarrow{\cong} R_{j,i}(\pi_j) \]
    such that
    \[ \phi_{j,k} \circ \phi_{i,j} = \phi_{i,k}; \text{ and} \]
    \item morphisms \( (\pi_i,\phi_{i,j})_{i,j} \to (P_i,\psi_{i,j})_{i,j} \) the data of a collection of principal \( G \)-bundle morphisms \( (f_i: P_i \to Q_i)_i \) over \( U_i \) such that on every double overlap \( U_{ij} \), \( \psi_{i,j} \circ f_j = f_i \circ \phi_{i,j} \).
\end{enumerate}
For principal \( G \)-bundle \( \pi: P \to X \), we are denoting the principal \( G \)-bundle (over \( U_i \)) \( \pi_{i}: \pi^{-1}(U_i) \to U_i) \) as \( P|_{U_i} \).

Given the functors (morphisms in \( \Grpd \)) \( F(X) \to F(U_i) \) induced by inclusion \( U_i \subseteq X \), the definition of limit, gives us a functor \( \Prin_G(X) = F(X) \xrightarrow{\rho} \Desc(\mathcal{U},F) \) that is unique up to unique isomorphism. For a principal \( G \)-bundle \( \pi: P \to X \), \( \rho(\pi) \) is the family \( (\pi|_{i},\phi_{i,j})_{i,j} \) where \( \phi_{i,j}: R_{i,j}(\pi_i) \to R_{j,i}(\pi_j) \) is the identity since \( R_{i,j}(\pi_i) = \pi^{-1}(U_{ij}) = R_{j,i}(\pi_j) \). Further, note that for any descent datum \((\pi_i,\phi_{i,j}) \in \text{Ob}(\Desc(\mathcal{U}, F))\), the cocycle condition implies \( \phi_{i,i} = \id \) and \( \phi_{j,i} = \phi_{i,j}^{-1} \).

We want to show that \( \rho \) is an equivalence of categories. First, we will see that \( \rho \) is full and faithful, ie fully faithful.

Consider two morphisms \( f,g: P \to Q \) of principal \( G \)-bundles over \( X \) and suppose \( \rho(f) = \rho(g) \). Then, for each \( i \),
\[ f|_{\pi^{-1}(U_i)} = g|_{\pi^{-1}(U_i)}. \]
But, \( P = \bigcup_i \pi^{-1}(U_i) \) because \( \{ U_i \} \) covers \( X \), so \( f \) and \( g \) agree on an open cover of \( P \) so \( f = g \). Thus, \( \rho \) is faithful.

Suppose we have principal \( G \)-bundles \( P,Q \in \Prin_G(X) = F(X) \) and morphism \( (f_i)_i: \rho(P) \to \rho(Q) \) in \( \Desc(\mathcal{U},F) \). So each \( f_i : P|_{U_i} \to Q|_{U_i} \) is a principal \( G \)-bundle morphism over \( U_i \), and the descent condition says that on overlaps \( U_{ij} \), the two restrictions agree under the canonical identifications. Since these identifications, as noted above, are just the obvious ones induced by \( U_{ij} \subseteq U_i \) and \( U_{ij} \subseteq U_j \), we have \( f_i = f_j \) on \( P|_{U_{ij}} \). Thus, we define \( f: P \to Q \) by
\[ f(p) = f_i(p) \qquad \text{ if } \pi(p) \in U_i, \]
which is well-defined on overlaps.

Note that \( f \) is continuous because \( \bigcup_i \pi^{-1}(U_i) \) is an open covering of \( P \) and \( f_i = f|_{\pi^{-1}(U_i)} \) is continuous. Further, note that
\[\begin{tikzcd}
	P && Q \\
	\\
	& U
	\arrow["f", from=1-1, to=1-3]
	\arrow[from=1-1, to=3-2]
	\arrow[from=1-3, to=3-2]
\end{tikzcd}\]
commutes for all \( i \), so
\[\begin{tikzcd}
	P && Q \\
	\\
	& X
	\arrow["f", from=1-1, to=1-3]
	\arrow[from=1-1, to=3-2]
	\arrow[from=1-3, to=3-2]
\end{tikzcd}\]
commutes. Similarly, \( f \)is \( G \)-equivariant on \( \pi^{-1}(U_i) \) for all \( i \), so \( f \) is \( G \)-equivariant on \( P \).

Thus, \( f \) is a principal \( G \)-bundle morphism. By construction \( \rho(f) = (f_i)_i \). Hence \( \rho \) is full.

Now, all that is left to show is that \( \rho \) is essentially surjective. Suppose \( (\pi: \P_i \to U_i,\phi_{i,j}) \in \text{Ob}(\Desc(\mathcal{U},F)) \). We want to construct a principal \( G \)-bundle on \( X \) whose local restrictions (to \( U_i \)) recover this descent datum. Define
\[ P:= \left( \bigsqcup_i P_i \right)/\sim \]
with equivalence relation \( p_i \sim \phi_{i,j}(p_i) \) for \( p_i \in P_i|_{U_{ij}} = \pi_i^{-1}(U_{ij}) \). Define \( \pi: P \to X \) by \( [p_i] \mapsto \pi_i(p_i) \) which is well-defined since if \( p_j = \phi_{i,j}(p_i) \), then \( \pi_j(p_j) = \pi_i(p_i) \) since \( \phi_{i,j} \) is a fiber bundle map over \( U_{ij} \).

Now, define a right \( G \)-action on \( P \) by \( [p_i]\cdot g := [p_i \cdot g] \). This is well-defined: suppose \( [p_i] = [p_j] \) so \( p_j = \phi_{i,j}(p_i) \) on \( U_{ij} \). Since \( \phi_{i,j} \) \( G \)-equivariant, \( p_j \cdot g = \phi_{i,j}(p_i) \cdot g = \phi_{i,j}(p_i \cdot g) \). Thus, \( p_i \cdot g \sim p_j \cdot g \), so \( [p_i \cdot g] = [p_j \cdot g] \), so indeed this action is well-defined.

For each \( i \), define \( \theta_i: P_i \to \pi^{-1} \) by \( p \mapsto [p] \). \( \theta_i \) preserves projection maps since \( \pi(\theta_i(p)) = \pi([p]) = \pi_i(p) \), and \( \theta_i \) respects the right \( G \)-action becasue for every \( p \in P_i \) and \( g \in G \), \( \theta_i(p\cdot g) = [p\cdot g] = [p] \cdot g = \theta_i(p)\cdot g \), so \( \theta_i \) is a morphism of principal \( G \)-bundles over \( U_i \). Its inverse \( \eta_i: \pi^{-1}(U_i) \to P_i \) given by \( [p_j] \mapsto \phi_{j,i}(p_j) \) is also a morphism of principle \( G \)-bundles over \( U_i \), so
\[ \eta_i: \pi^{-1}(U_i) \xrightarrow{\cong} P_i \]
in \( \Prin_G(U_i) \).

Thus, the restriction of \( \pi:P \to X \) to \( U_i \) is exactly the given bundle \( \pi_i:P_i\to U_i \). Since \( \pi_i \) is a principal \( G \)-bundle, for each \( x\in U_i \), there exists open \( x \in V_x \subseteq U_i \) such that there exists \( \alpha_x: P_i|_{V_x} \xrightarrow{\cong} V_x \times G \) in \( \Prin_G(V_x) \). Thus, we define \( h_x:= \alpha_x \circ \eta_i: P|_{V_x} = \pi^{-1}(V_x) \xrightarrow{\cong} V_x \times G \). Thus, for any \( x \in X \), choose \( U_i \ni x \) and then see there exists open \( x\in V_x \subseteq U_i \subseteq X \) such that \( \pi: P \to X \) looks like \( V_x \times G \) over \( V_x \).

On an overlap \( V_x \cap V_y \) with \( x \in U_i \) and \( y \in U_j \), \( h_x h_y^{-1} = \alpha_x \circ \eta_i\theta_j \circ \alpha_y^{-1} = \alpha_x \circ \phi_{j,i} \circ \alpha_y^{-1} \), which is an isomorphism of principal \( G \)-bundles over \( V_x \cap V_y \). Thus, it lies over the identity and commutes with the right \( G \)-action, so it must be of the form \( (u,g) \mapsto (u,g_{xy}(u)g) \) for a continuous \( g_{xy}: V_x \cap V_y \to G \). Thus, \( \pi: P \to X \) is a principal \( G \)-bundle over \( X \), and we have that \( \rho \) is essentially surjective.

Thus, we conclude, \( \rho \) is fully faithful and essentially surjective, so it is a equivalence of categories. Hence, \( F \) is a stack as desired.
\end{example}

Recall that when we were studying sheaves, we had the notion of a presheaf. Every sheaf was a presheaf and this inclusion had an adjoint called sheafification. That is, given any presheaf (functor) \( F: \Open(X)^\op \to \Ab \), we can sheafify to get a sheaf \( F^\sharp \). There is a similar process here. Any stack is a prestack and this inclusion gives an adjoint called stackification. The notion of a prestack is in fact much more complicated than that of a presheaf, though. Hence, although we can stackify any prestack, we will just define stackfication over functors into \( \Grpd \) from a site. That is, things that would feasibly descend to a stack in the way we have described it above.

\textcolor{blue}{Define weak equivalence}
\begin{theorem}[Adapted from \cite{moerdijk2002introductionlanguagestacksgerbes}]
    Suppose \( F: \Open(X)^\op \to \Grpd \). Then, there exists an associated stack \( \hat{F} \). That is, there exists a stack \( \hat{F} \) and a weak equivalence \( F \to \hat{F} \).
\end{theorem}
\begin{proof}
    Most concisely, we can define the associated stack as a 2-colimit:
    \[ \hat{F} = \colim_{\mathcal{U} \in \Cov(X)} \Desc(\mathcal{U},F). \]
    More concretely, define \( \hat{F}(X) \) as follows:
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item an object consists of a cover \( \mathcal{U} = \{ U_i \} \) of \( X \) and an object \( (a,\theta) \) of \( \Desc(\mathcal{U},F) \), and
        \item for two such objects \( (a,\theta) \) of \( \Desc(\mathcal{U},F) \) and \( (b,\rho) \) of \( \Desc(\mathcal{V},F) \) for open covers \( \mathcal{U} = \{ U_i \}, \mathcal{V} = \{ V_i \} \) of \( X \), a morphism \( (a,\theta) \xrightarrow{f} (b,\rho) \) consists of a system of morphisms
        \[ f_{\alpha,\beta}: a_{\alpha}|_{U_\alpha \cap V_\beta} \to b_\beta|_{U_\alpha \cap V_\beta} \]
    \end{enumerate}
    such that for any \( \alpha,\alpha' \in A \) and \( \beta,\beta' \in B \), the diagram
    \[\begin{tikzcd}
    	{a_\alpha|_{U_{\alpha\alpha'}\cap V_{\beta\beta'}}} && {b_{\beta}|_{U_{\alpha\alpha'}\cap V_{\beta\beta'}}} \\
    	\\
    	{a_{\alpha'}|_{U_{\alpha\alpha'}\cap V_{\beta\beta'}}} && {b_{\beta'}|_{U_{\alpha\alpha'}\cap V_{\beta\beta'}}}
    	\arrow["{f_{\alpha,\beta}}", from=1-1, to=1-3]
    	\arrow["{\theta_{\alpha \alpha'}}"{description}, from=3-1, to=1-1]
    	\arrow["{f_{\alpha',\beta'}}", from=3-1, to=3-3]
    	\arrow["{\rho_{\beta\beta'}}"{description}, from=3-3, to=1-3]
    \end{tikzcd}\]
    commutes.
\end{proof}

\begin{example}[Constant Stack]
    Suppose \( F : \Open(X)^\op \to \Grpd \) is constant. Then, the constant stack is the associated stack of \( F \).
\end{example}

